127. Metapnor. Metaphors abound in Juvenal, and even mixed metaphors are not rare: αθ. 7, 39 f. dulcedine famae succensus ; 7, 54f.; 8, 76 f. Many of the more striking metaphors are satiric rather than poetic : e. θ. 3‚150 f. cicatrix and vulnus (of a mended shoe); 5, 169 stricto pane ; 4, 77 vilicus urbi (= praefectus). He is especially fond of metaphors drawn from the military sphere and from the sports of the amphitheatre: αθ. 7, 173 ad puynam qui rhetorica descendit ab umbra ; 1 1, 89 domito referens a monte liyonem ; 14, 230 f. iolas effundit habenas curriculo ; cf. notes on 14, 230, 246.’

128. Simile. Juvenal's comparisons are usually drawn ftom history, mythology, or the realm of nature and animal life: αθ. 1, 43 f. palleatr ut nudis pressit qui calcibus an- quem, aut Luyudunensem rhetor dicturus ad aram ,· 3, 279 f. noctem patitur lucentis amicam Pelidae ; 6, 270 (uxor) orba tiyride peior.⁸

129. Metonymy. The usual types occur:

a. Abstract for concrete: αθ. 1, 34 nobilitas (= nobiles); 1, 110 honor ( = tribunus).⁴

b. Effect for cause: αθ. 5, 120 nequa indiynatio desit; 1, 120 fumas (firewood).

c. Material for thing made: αθ. 1, 28 aarum (a ring); 14, 194 buxus (a comb).

d. Container for thing contained: αθ. 11, 38 deficiente
